# CAP theorem

- During a network partition, choose between consistency (CP) and availability (AP) — both is impossible.
- Strong consistency (CP): financial transactions, inventory, auth sessions — accept downtime during partitions.
- High availability (AP): social feeds, analytics, caches — accept stale reads during partitions.
- Most systems are neither pure CP nor AP — tune per operation (strong writes, eventual reads).
- Document consistency guarantees per endpoint in API docs.
- Use eventual consistency with conflict resolution (CRDTs, last-write-wins, vector clocks) when appropriate.
- Health checks should detect partition scenarios, not just process crashes.
- Do not assume single-node databases scale horizontally without CAP tradeoffs.
- Test split-brain scenarios in staging for distributed systems.
- Prefer single-region strong consistency until multi-region requirements are proven.
